The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 GAIL net profit rises 18%

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, April 28: GAIL (India) Limited has posted an 18 per cent increase in net profit at Rs 2,310 crore for the financial year ended March 31, 2006 against Rs 1,954 crore in the previous year.

 The companys turnover went up to Rs 14,460 crore from Rs. 12,412 crore in the previous financial year.

 The increase in profit comes even after GAIL had to pay Rs 1,064 crore as its share of the subsidy on domestic LPG and kerosene supplied through the public distribution system.

 The price for the gas used by the company has also gone up from Rs 2,850 to Rs 6,740 per 1000 standard cubic metres with effect from July 1, 2005. 

 During 2005-06, revenues from natural gas transmission increased by 12 per cent to Rs 2,034 crore from Rs 1,810 crore in the previous year. 

 Revenues from gas trading increased by 18 per cent to Rs 8,401 crore from Rs 7,129 crore in the previous year. Revenues from LPG and other liquid hydrocarbons increased by 31 per cent to Rs 2,062 crore from Rs 1,578 crore mainly because of an increase in prices.

 The quantity of natural gas carried through the GAIL pipeline network increased 10 per cent during the year to 78.87 million standard cubic metres per day (MMSCMD) from 71.56 MMSCMD.

 During the fourth quarter of 2005-06, the companys turnover increased 11 per cent to Rs 3,660 crore from Rs 3,285 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous financial year. The net profit during the fourth quarter was Rs 409 crore, which was 22 per cent lower than the net profit of Rs 524 crore during the corresponding quarter of the previous financial year.

 During the fourth quarter, gas transmission increased by 8 per cent to 78.34 MMSCMD from 72.46 MMSCMD during the corresponding quarter of the previous financial year.

 The companys market capitalisation on March 31 was Rs. 26,913 crore, an increase of 50 per cent over that on March 31, 2005.

 Sterlite Optical net soars

 Sterlite Optical Technologies, an optical cable manufacturer, has posted an eight-fold increase in net profit at Rs 22.4 crore for the quarter ended March 31 compared with Rs 2.86 crore in the corresponding period last year.

 The companys income for the quarter under review grew 26 per cent to Rs 146.6 crore from Rs 115.9 crore in the year-ago period, it has informed the Bombay Stock Exchange. The board has recommended a dividend of Re 0.5 on a share of Rs 5 each (10 per cent) for the year.

 For the year ended March 31, its net profit stood at Rs 40.7 crore against Rs 10.2 crore in 2004-05. 




